1.0     Executive Summary



Air Liquide Large Industries US, L.P. (Air Liquide) operates a hydrogen plant within the Chevron refinery located in El Segundo, California (Hydrogen Facility). This document addresses the requirements of the United States Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA) Risk Management Plan (RMP) and the California Accidental Release Prevention (CaIARP) program with regards to the hydrogen processes on site. The following summarizes the required elements of a Program 1 facility.



1.1     ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE POLICIES

"Our commitment to Safety and Environmental Protection in the Air Liquide, El Segundo Hydrogen Plant must extend beyond the gates. As part of the community, we have a responsibility to our customers and to those who live in the surrounding area to help provide a safe working and living environment. Through safety, concern for the environment, and community involvement, we can develop a true partnership with our customers and neighbors."



The Hydrogen Facility has accidental release protection programs for all covered processes, which includes a prevention program with the following elements:

?    Maintaining up-to-date safety information;

?    Conducting a process hazard analysis;

?    Implementing operating procedures;

?    Implementing a staff training program;

?    Implementing a maintenance program;

?    Conducting compliance audits; and

?    Conducting incident investigations.



An Emergency Action Plan has been developed to help instruct personnel how to respond in case of an emergency. Emergency response actions involve the system operators and maintenance staff, as well as the local El Segundo Fire Department. In addition, the Plant Manager or an appointed representative serves as the focal point during and following an accidental release for notifying the Chevron El Segundo Refinery, reporting to the appropriate agencies, and providing information to the public.



1.2     DESCRIPTION OF THE STATIONARY SOURCE

o the CalARP and EPA RMP regulations, processes at the Hydrogen Facility are also subject to the OSHA Process Safety Management (PSM) standard. Although not required for Program 1 facilities under Ca1ARP and EPA RMP regulations, a prevention program has been developed by the Hydrogen Facility that includes the following elements (also indicates the applicable internal regulation number):

?    Employee participation in process safety management and accident prevention (PSM - Employee Participation, 2B-LIPSM-ADM-0319-P);             

?    Process safety information to address chemical properties and associated hazards,

equipment design/configuration information, specific chemical inventories and

operation limits for key process parameters (El Segundo SMR Process Safety

Information for PSM/RMP/Ca1ARP Covered Processes, 3-ELSSMR-HS-0005-Y);

?    Process hazard analysis to help ensure that hazards associated with the various processes are identified and controlled (Implementing Process Hazard Analysis, 2B-LI-ORM-0008-P);

?    Maintenance of written operating procedures that address various modes of process operations (PSM/RMP Annual Review and Certification of Operating Documents, 2B-LIPSM-OPS-0300-P);

?    Implementation of a formal training program for all employees involved in operating the process (El Segundo SMR Training Matrix, 3-ELSSMR-TRN-0001-T);

?    Pre-startup safety reviews of new/modified facilities or processes before placing those facilities or processes into service (Large Industries Pre-Startup Safety Review, 2B-LI-ORM-0003-P);

?    Practices and procedures to ensure mechanical integrity and to maintain pressure vessels, piping systems, relief valve and vent systems, controls, pumps, compressors, and emergency shutdown systems in a safe operating condition (El Segundo SMR RMP Mechanical Integrity, 3-ELSSMR-OPS-1004-P);

?    Safe work practices in place to help ensure employee and process safety. The facilities Life Critical procedures include the following (Safe Work Permit,

 2-ALL-HSS-0220-P, Hot Work,, 2-ALL-HSS-0200-P, El Energy Control and Isolation, 2-ALL-HSS-0260-P-1, Confined Space Entry, 2-ALL-HSS-0240-P and Process Line Break, 2-ALL-HSS-0200-P);

?    Management of change requirements for ensuring that proposed process or equipment changes or changes indirectly affecting processes are evaluated, approved and documented prior to implementation (Large Industries Management of Change, 2B-LI-ORM-0002-P);

?    Incident investigation and reporting to proactively identify root causes and correct them rather than simply addressing the symptom of the incident (Large Industries Reliability, Safety, PSI, PSSI and Near Miss, 2B-LI-OPS-0018-P);

?    Compliance audits to help ensure the accident prevention program is functioning properly (PSM/RMP Compliance Audit, 2B-LI-AUD-0303-P); and 

?    Contractors pre-qualification and assessment process in place to ensure the safety of our contractors and  communicate process safety risk prior to initiation of work  (Large Industries Contractor Safety, 2B-LI-HS-0010-P0)



1.5     CHEMICAL SPECIFIC PREVENTION STEPS

The processes at the Hydrogen Facility have hazards that must be managed to ensure continued safe operation. The accident prevention program summarized in Section 1.4 is applied to CalARP/RMP covered flammable mixture process in the Hydrogen Facility. These prevention program activities help prevent potential accident scenarios that could be caused by (1) equipment failures and (2) human errors.

In addition to the accidental release prevention program, the Hydrogen Facility has safety features designed to (1) quickly detect the release, (2) contain/control the release; (3) reduce the consequence of (mitigate) a release.



